output:
Let's solve the system of equations by the substitution or elimination method. Here we will use the elimination method.
Multiply the second equation by 2 so x will have the same coefficient in both equations.
$$\begin{array}{r}3 x+4 y=-23 \\4 y-2 x=-38\end{array}$$
Add the two equations to eliminate x.
$$\begin{array}{r}3 x+4 y=-23 \\4 y-2 x=-38\end{array} \\ \Rightarrow \begin{array}{r}3 x+4 y+4 y-2 x=-23-38 \\ \Rightarrow 5 x+2 y=-61 \end{array}$$
Now substitute y from the second equation into the new equation above.
$$\begin{array}{r}2 y-x=-19 \\ \Rightarrow y=\frac{19+x}{2}\end{array}$$
$$\Rightarrow \begin{array}{r}5 x+2 \left(\frac{19+x}{2}\right)=-61 \\ \Rightarrow 5 x+19+x=-61 \\ \Rightarrow 6 x=-42 \\ \Rightarrow x=-7\end{array}$$
Now find y.
$$\Rightarrow y=\frac{19+x}{2}=\frac{19+(-7)}{2}=\frac{12}{2}=-6$$
The solution is $(x, y) = (-7, -6)$.
The answerD$(9,-6)$.
